                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">So, I had a strange situation. I stayed with a friend for a week, she invited me over, she lives 4 hours from where I was living at the time. Anyhow, she asked me one day to wake her up when I was ready to go. NP, she slept with her door open, so I figured I'd just go knock on it and call her name, and we'd head out to the amusement park.
<br />

<br />
Well, I got to her door, and she was masturbating. So, I just left for a while, and came back. Didn't bother me one way or another. Well, she is of a religious belief that extremely frowns upon that. I never mentioned it, because... um, well, why would I suddenly blurt out, "Hey I saw you masturbating"? Like, who cares. Wasn't even an akward moment, she didn't even know I was there.
<br />

<br />
So, fast forward a year to last night, and she calls me (we've kept in touch), and starts crying over the phone. She starts telling me that she's done something horrifyingly bad and was afraid people would find out, they'd hate her forever, and she'd go to hell, blah blah. Over the course of the conversation, she finally tells me she masturbates, then hangs up abruptly amidst tears, only saying she'll call me again tonight.
<br />

<br />
My delimma is this. I KNOW I am going to have to have a "heart to heart" with her. I am the person she goes to for all sorts of advice (god help her  ), and I know that tonight, when she calls back, it will be to see how I react to her horrifying, shocking news. 
<br />

<br />
Now, two things. Since it's a religious taboo for her, what should I say about it? To me, now, having left that particular taboo behind a while ago, it's a natural, simple, obvious function of having sexual organs. But I understand that for her, this is traumatic, that she is having to come to terms with this in some way right now. I don't know if I should tell her to let her religion lead her, or if I should tell her my own opinion.
<br />

<br />
The second issue I have is, should I tell her, "I saw you when I was visiting, and not only don't I feel any different towards you, but I didn't even care about it"? Or should I just not even mention it for fear she will feel even more embarassed?
<br />

<br />
I remember going through this time myself, and how scared I was that I'd be caught, so I don't really know how to approach it. I don't know if it would be worse for her to know I'd "caught her" or for her to think that she'll be unloved and unwanted if she "gets caught." And I'm not sure if it's a sexual crisis, or a crisis of faith.
<br />

<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/eusa_doh.gif" alt="eusa_doh.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
By the way. I have to add here that i also think she may be Bi, if not even gay. I would almost suspect that she was hoping a year ago that I WOULD catch her at it. But I am not certain, and I really don't want her to get the idea that I am into that (I'm very straight), but at the same time, I don't want her to get the idea that I think it's bad or wrong (because I don't).
<br />

<br />
I am really feeling lost here as to what to do.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=391428" target="_blank" class="postlink"><span style="color: purple">Magelo</span></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
