<br />
My suspicion is she has no idea.. Put simply, she sounds like a sexual person who has been repressed by her religion. Whether she is gay or straight is a moot point, but I wouldn't rule out her being straight but attracted to you as a mentor figure. Clearly she looks up to you with regard to sexuality. Perhaps, in the past, you told her that you masturbate and/or are sexually active. The fact that you were staying over probably gave her the courage to masturbate without guilt (a rare event I would bet) because she believes that you aren't going to hell so how could she too, right? The point is that while I have no doubt she did it because you were there I wouldn't necessarily assume she desired to be caught.. 
<br />

<br />
As to the problem. IMPO (and please don't flame me for this - it's just my opinion).. Spirituality is an amazing amazing thing. It's wonderful and grand and can bring people a lot of joy. This is the 'faith' part of religion. But there is another side of religion, IMPO, that is the political side. It is the side that kept literacy from the masses, appointed Kings as the 'solitary, living representation of God,' lead to the Crusades, etc. etc. etc. As Tom Robbins says religion is one person's spirituality, mass produced. Again, IMPO, the sexual tabuus are in this same political arena. Furthermore, they are somewhat unique to America.
<br />

<br />
Christian Europe (with the possible but definately hypocritical exception of England) does not view sex in the same way we do. We are a country founded by Puritans and those beliefs have held on to this day. Those Puritans weren't very keen on women. They weren't very keen on gays. They weren't very keen on non-procreative sex (if you use birth control or have *any* sex other than missionary position for the sole purpose of conception you might want to read up on US religious political movements/laws/propositions before quote the Bible at anyone else). Sex was the *punishment* God gave Adam and Eve in the eyes of the fire and brimstone religions that spawned US thought on the subject.
<br />

<br />
So in telling her how to deal with this I, personally, would NOT advise her to follow her religion. That's just sentencing her to years of more turmoil, self-doubt and dejection. You could, however, encourage her to explore both her body and her faith. I'm not sure what resources are out there in your area but I'm sure they exist. If nothing else, try investigating European thoughts on the subject (I would avoid Latin countries where the Madonna and the whore syndrome is still far too common) and try to help her bridge a sense of self-assured security while still maintaining her faith. As a starting place, Good Vibrations might has some books on the subject of religious tabuu and sexuality. Many of these probably will be too anti-religion for your needs but I'm sure one or two would be a good fit.
<br />

<br />
